00:05:18.270 --> 00:05:23.990
invite people to raise issues, to challenge
things I might have said.

00:05:23.990 --> 00:05:28.720
The fact that you're around for a long time
does not necessarily give you vision.

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:33.470
In fact, in some respects, if you've been
around for a long time, you can't necessarily

00:05:33.470 --> 00:05:38.009
either predict the future or see what's coming.
There is -- I forget who said this, but he

00:05:38.009 --> 00:05:43.990
said, you know, if an old and distinguished
scientist tells you you can do that, the chances

00:05:43.990 --> 00:05:47.539
are pretty good that you can.
But if that same individual says you can't

00:05:47.539 --> 00:05:52.330
do that, there's a good chance he's wrong.
So I may be wrong about some of the things

00:05:52.330 --> 00:05:56.070
I'm going to say.
And I invite some interaction about that.

00:05:56.070 --> 00:06:01.060
Let me start out by just reminding you that
the thing that you're working with started

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:06.891
out in a predecessor program called ARPANET
with four nodes, just four computers and four

00:06:06.891 --> 00:06:12.140
routers or, actually, packet switches.
I used to be at UCLA as a graduate student.

00:06:12.140 --> 00:06:18.280
And had the responsibility for writing the
software to connect a Sigma 7 computer to

00:06:18.280 --> 00:06:24.349
the first router that was installed at UCLA
in September of 1969.

00:06:24.349 --> 00:06:27.930
The Sigma is in a museum somewhere.
And some people think I should be there along

00:06:27.930 --> 00:06:29.190
with it.
[ Laughter. ]

00:06:29.190 --> 00:06:34.660
