00:07:39.050 --> 00:07:41.639
Okay.
Are we square on that?

00:07:41.639 --> 00:07:43.240
See, it's okay to interact.
[ Laughter ]

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:46.000
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: Somebody throw the -- all right.
[ Laughter ]

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:51.330
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: All right.
So that's -- the point here is that it is

00:07:51.330 --> 00:07:59.240
voluntarily a collaboration of global proportions.
This doesn't happen unless a lot of people

00:07:59.240 --> 00:08:04.110
want it to happen.
So an important other takeaway is even though

00:08:04.110 --> 00:08:08.290
Bob Kahn and I did do the original design
work, this wouldn't have happened if, literally,

00:08:08.290 --> 00:08:13.629
millions of people didn't decide they wanted
it to happen.

00:08:13.629 --> 00:08:17.680
Here's just kind of a picture of how quickly
the number of machines on the network has

00:08:17.680 --> 00:08:22.620
grown over time.
It started out in -- with the four nodes that

00:08:22.620 --> 00:08:27.150
I mentioned on the ARPANET.
When the network was first -- Internet was

00:08:27.150 --> 00:08:33.800
first released, it was January of 1983, there
were 400 computers on the network in January

00:08:33.800 --> 00:08:36.890
of '83.
And it was a hard problem to get everybody

00:08:36.890 --> 00:08:41.130
to switch over from the older NCP protocols
to the TCP/IP protocols.

00:08:41.130 --> 00:08:43.350
And I don't want to waste your time telling
you how we did that.

00:08:43.350 --> 00:08:46.160
But it was coercive.
It was not cooperative.

00:08:46.160 --> 00:08:50.649
It was one of those I'm turning your funding
off if you don't switch over to TCP/IP.

00:08:50.649 --> 00:08:53.770
Fortunately, I was at DARPA at the time and
could actually say that.

00:08:53.770 --> 00:08:56.470
Today you can't do that.
That's harder.

00:08:56.470 --> 00:09:02.930
The number of machines on the net now that
are publicly visible is approaching 750 million.

00:09:02.930 --> 00:09:06.180
The number of machines on the Net, in fact,
is much larger than that.

00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:09.660
We're an example, because there are lots of
machines behind firewalls that people can't

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:14.740
see through the public DNS.
The number of users now is estimated by Internet

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:19.230
world stats at 1.8 billion.
Again, that's an estimate.

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:24.010
The other thing which has been going on that
we are all very much participant in is the

00:09:24.010 --> 00:09:27.210
mobiles that have shown up in the telecom
environment.

00:09:27.210 --> 00:09:32.771
Extremely rapid innovation and penetration.
A lot of those mobiles are Internet-enabled.

00:09:32.771 --> 00:09:37.260
And, of course, we care a lot about that because
we've offered Android as an operating system,

00:09:37.260 --> 00:09:42.360
and we are wanting very much to offer and
let others offer applications that take advantage

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:47.040
of mobile access to the network.
If we look at where the Internet is right

00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:52.650
now, or where the users are, it's actually
a fairly stunning revelation that North America

00:09:52.650 --> 00:09:56.640
is only third on the list now.
It used to be at the top, because this is

00:09:56.640 --> 00:10:00.810
where the first penetration occurred.
We're still the highest percentage penetrated.

00:10:00.810 --> 00:10:04.270
But as you can see, Asia represents the largest
single grouping.

00:10:04.270 --> 00:10:12.010
And of the 764 million people on the Net in
Asia, about half of them are in mainland China.

00:10:12.010 --> 00:10:16.410
So the largest grouping of users on the Internet
today is in China.

00:10:16.410 --> 00:10:20.380
Now, we all recognize that there have been
interactions between Google and China and

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:25.520
there's policy questions.
But it is an inescapable fact that the largest

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:28.160
population of users on the Net today is in
China.

00:10:28.160 --> 00:10:32.660
And that will continue to grow, because their
percentage penetration, Asian penetration,

00:10:32.660 --> 00:10:37.210
is only 20%.
So you understand when it gets to 75 or 76%,

00:10:37.210 --> 00:10:41.680
the number will be dramatically bigger.
We care a lot about these kinds of statistics

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:46.320
because it tells us where our products and
services have to go, where they have to serve,

00:10:46.320 --> 00:10:51.280
what kinds of users, cultures, languages,
scripts, and everything else we have to be

00:10:51.280 --> 00:10:54.170
prepared to deal with.
These are just another way of displaying the

00:10:54.170 --> 00:10:57.850
same kind of information.
So I'll kind of skip through all of that.

00:10:57.850 --> 00:11:01.690
You'll notice at the bottom here that the
average penetration around the world is slightly

00:11:01.690 --> 00:11:05.530
over 26%.
As the chief Internet evangelist at Google,

00:11:05.530 --> 00:11:08.290
I have the feeling I have three-quarters of
the world to convert still.

00:11:08.290 --> 00:11:12.620
There's a lot of work to be done to get Internet
in place.

00:11:12.620 --> 00:11:18.900
Mobiles are actually helping a lot in some
respects, because their economics is so attractive.

00:11:18.900 --> 00:11:24.930
When Bob Kahn started this -- I want to emphasize,
it was Bob Kahn that started the project.

00:11:24.930 --> 00:11:27.360
He was at the Defense Advanced Research Projects
Agency.

00:11:27.360 --> 00:11:33.710
I was still at Stanford.
And he had some simple ideas about what he

00:11:33.710 --> 00:11:37.820
wanted to accomplish in the interconnection
of networks.

00:11:37.820 --> 00:11:43.020
Each network would have to stand on its own.
There wouldn't be any changes permitted to

00:11:43.020 --> 00:11:46.910
the networks that were part of the original
Internet in order to make them part of the

00:11:46.910 --> 00:11:49.680
Internet.
Which led to the need for gateways in between.

00:11:49.680 --> 00:11:52.350
Because the networks had no way of referring
to any other nets.

00:11:52.350 --> 00:11:56.560
Their addressing structure thought they were
the only network in the world.

00:11:56.560 --> 00:12:00.360
Later on, we'll see a similar situation coming
up with clouds.

00:12:00.360 --> 00:12:04.010
This is all best efforts communication.
And in a sense, that was really important.

00:12:04.010 --> 00:12:07.240
We made no guarantees at all.
If you could get a packet from point A to

00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:11.760
point B with some probability greater than
zero, that's all we were asking of the underlying

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:16.140
system.
There would be these black boxes, which we

00:12:16.140 --> 00:12:20.940
called gateways at the time, because we didn't
know they were supposed to be called routers,

00:12:20.940 --> 00:12:27.230
and we assumed they would be able to send
objects, packets, through each of the networks

00:12:27.230 --> 00:12:32.620
that interconnected and that the Internet
packets would be encapsulated inside those

00:12:32.620 --> 00:12:36.080
packets of each individual network.
That turned out to be a very important tactic,

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:40.970
because it allowed arbitrarily large numbers
of different kinds of packet networks to be

00:12:40.970 --> 00:12:45.580
part of the system, because we were simply
encapsulating and decapsulating the Internet

00:12:45.580 --> 00:12:49.520
packets that went end to end.
And, finally, there's no global control at

00:12:49.520 --> 00:12:53.310
the operational level.
That was important from the military point

00:12:53.310 --> 00:12:58.100
of view, because we didn't want a central
place that could be attacked and the network

00:12:58.100 --> 00:13:01.750
disabled.
So there's global addressing was needed, because

00:13:01.750 --> 00:13:04.000
the networks didn't have a way of referring
to other nets.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:08.630
Gateways were forwarding packets.
There were algorithms to recover from lost

00:13:08.630 --> 00:13:10.730
packets.
We didn't assume everything was reliable.

00:13:10.730 --> 00:13:14.560
And some of the initial networks that were
involved were actually quite unreliable.

00:13:14.560 --> 00:13:20.040
Packet radio was a mobile system.
Ethernet was not necessarily a reliable transmission

00:13:20.040 --> 00:13:23.210
scheme.
We provided pipelining so that there could

00:13:23.210 --> 00:13:28.080
be a stream of packets flowing from end to
end, which is where those of you doing TCP

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:32.790
stuff know about Windows, about how many packets
can be outstanding before you have to stop

00:13:32.790 --> 00:13:34.710
and wait.
There were some end-to-end check zones.

00:13:34.710 --> 00:13:40.470
We assumed things would be reassembled.
We knew we needed host flow control, although

00:13:40.470 --> 00:13:45.620
we'll see that we didn't do as good a job
then as we could probably do now.

00:13:45.620 --> 00:13:48.830
And then interfacing to a variety of operating
systems and other things.

00:13:48.830 --> 00:13:53.280
There were some other secondary concerns like
efficiency, performance, and, by the way,

00:13:53.280 --> 00:14:00.050
security, although, in fact, we didn't focus
very heavily at all on security, and we might

00:14:00.050 --> 00:14:03.460
look back on that and regret it.
But I have to say that if we had tried to

00:14:03.460 --> 00:14:09.010
focus heavily on security in these early days,
we might never have even gotten anything built

00:14:09.010 --> 00:14:12.520
that we could test.
We honestly did not know whether this system

00:14:12.520 --> 00:14:17.040
would actually work.
One of the nice things about the Net is that

00:14:17.040 --> 00:14:22.591
we didn't make any assumptions about applications.
And, you know, the old expression, if you

00:14:22.591 --> 00:14:27.110
don't know where you're going, any road will
take you there, if you don't know what application

00:14:27.110 --> 00:14:31.820
you're running, any packet will take you there.
And in a very funny way, the Internet has

00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:37.920
survived and thrived because of the fact that
it wasn't designed to do any particular thing.

00:14:37.920 --> 00:14:42.280
A lot of the historical networks, like the
telephone, telegraph net, the television broadcast

00:14:42.280 --> 00:14:47.470
networks, the cable networks, were purpose-designed.
And that purpose design limited what they

00:14:47.470 --> 00:14:50.320
could do.
The Internet didn't have that limitation.

00:14:50.320 --> 00:14:57.580
And as the capacity of the Net has grown,
as the economics of electronics has dropped,

00:14:57.580 --> 00:15:02.110
it's been possible to make the packet-switched
net do a lot more than it did when we were

00:15:02.110 --> 00:15:10.090
working, you know, with 50 kilobit backbones.
I mean, the word 50 kilobit and backbone in

00:15:10.090 --> 00:15:13.950
the same sentence sounds, excuse me?
That's a dialup modem today.

00:15:13.950 --> 00:15:18.870
The other thing that's interesting is, the
Internet layer, the Internet packets, have

00:15:18.870 --> 00:15:21.700
no idea what they're carrying.
They don't know how they're being carried.

00:15:21.700 --> 00:15:27.800
They don't care if it goes over a satellite
link, an optical fiber, or submarine cable.

00:15:27.800 --> 00:15:32.290
Only the edge devices that can interpret the
contents of the packets understand what it

00:15:32.290 --> 00:15:38.740
means.
There is no national indicator in the I.P.

00:15:38.740 --> 00:15:41.560
address space.
That was a deliberate decision on my part.

00:15:41.560 --> 00:15:45.040
Remember, I'm doing this at the Defense Department
or for the Defense Department.

00:15:45.040 --> 00:15:51.480
I wanted not to have any binding of the networks
to any particular geographical location.

00:15:51.480 --> 00:15:56.820
Now, we all understand that the domain name
system has a very specific potential binding,

00:15:56.820 --> 00:16:00.220
because we have, you know, country codes,
like .DE, .FR.

00:16:00.220 --> 00:16:06.710
And a lot of us have worked hard to make it
possible to associate locale with I.P. addresses

00:16:06.710 --> 00:16:13.740
because we're interested in geographic -- applications
that have some knowledge of geographic location.

00:16:13.740 --> 00:16:18.040
But when the design was done, I didn't want
to have any such binding, because I didn't

00:16:18.040 --> 00:16:22.050
want any national authority to interfere with
the military's ability to deploy a network

00:16:22.050 --> 00:16:25.320
wherever it needed to go.
I didn't want some third party to say, "I'm

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:31.810
sorry, you can't have address space because
we think you're an aggressor or an enemy."

00:16:31.810 --> 00:16:37.350
So I didn't want that to be a problem.
And, finally, our performance targets, again,

00:16:37.350 --> 00:16:41.220
were best efforts.
Now, there are some changes going on in the

00:16:41.220 --> 00:16:43.810
Net.
And we're involved in some of them very intimately.

00:16:43.810 --> 00:16:47.010
IPv6 is one.
And I'll show you a chart that motivates why

00:16:47.010 --> 00:16:51.740
we need to have a different I.P. address space
than the IPv4.

00:16:51.740 --> 00:16:55.180
Some of the people in this room -- I saw Lorenzo
here.

00:16:55.180 --> 00:16:59.010
I don't know if Eric is here.
But you have some -- a group of people here

00:16:59.010 --> 00:17:04.220
at Google that have single-handedly pushed
us to implement IPv6.

00:17:04.220 --> 00:17:09.179
The reason that's so important is that the
IPv4 address space only has 32 bits.

00:17:09.179 --> 00:17:16.170
It's 4.3 billion terminations.
I made the decision in 1977 that the address

00:17:16.170 --> 00:17:20.860
space could be 32 bits and it would be enough.
I thought we were doing an experiment.

00:17:20.860 --> 00:17:23.800
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: I thought, you know, that we

00:17:23.800 --> 00:17:27.280
didn't know if this thing was going to work,
and surely 4.3 billion terminations is enough

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:30.080
for an experiment.
I mean, even the Defense Department probably

00:17:30.080 --> 00:17:35.370
couldn't use that many termination points.
So I thought what would happen is if we demonstrated

00:17:35.370 --> 00:17:40.030
this capability, then we would in fact do
a production engineering job of it.

00:17:40.030 --> 00:17:44.220
Well, the experiment never ended.
Here it is 2010, we're running out of address

00:17:44.220 --> 00:17:48.530
space, we need larger address space.
We actually argued 32 bits, 128 bits, and

00:17:48.530 --> 00:17:52.100
variable length.
The variable-length guys lost, because the

00:17:52.100 --> 00:17:55.750
programmers said it's going to chew up a bunch
of computer cycles to find the fields and

00:17:55.750 --> 00:17:59.260
the packets, and so they didn't want to do
that, so that was out the door.

00:17:59.260 --> 00:18:04.200
And finally, because nobody could make up
their minds and I'm sitting there in the Defense

00:18:04.200 --> 00:18:08.650
Department trying to get this program to move
ahead, we haven't built anything, I said,

00:18:08.650 --> 00:18:09.690
it's 32 bits.
That's it.

00:18:09.690 --> 00:18:11.690
Let's go do something.
Here we are.

00:18:11.690 --> 00:18:12.760
My fault.
[ Laughter ]

00:18:12.760 --> 00:18:19.130
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: On the other hand, you know,
if I had stood up and said we need 128 bits

00:18:19.130 --> 00:18:22.971
of address space because this is going to
be the world's backbone in 25 or 30 years,

00:18:22.971 --> 00:18:27.800
they'd look at me and say, "Boy, are you out
of --" internationalized domain names.

00:18:27.800 --> 00:18:31.661
Remember I showed you all the distribution
of users in the Internet?

00:18:31.661 --> 00:18:36.940
There are more users who don't use Latin character
sets than there are people who use Latin character

00:18:36.940 --> 00:18:38.732
sets.
So internationalized domain names are a way

00:18:38.732 --> 00:18:41.880
of writing domain names in scripts other than
Latin characters.

00:18:41.880 --> 00:18:48.700
So Cyrillic and Chinese and Hebrew and Arabic
and so on are all scripts that are now available

00:18:48.700 --> 00:18:52.190
for IDNs.
And they're being introduced now by the Internet

00:18:52.190 --> 00:18:56.460
Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers.
The domain name system, as I'm sure you are

00:18:56.460 --> 00:19:00.010
all very well aware, has got a bunch of vulnerabilities
in it.

00:19:00.010 --> 00:19:05.960
One aspect of that is that it's possible to
poison the cache of a DNS resolver.

00:19:05.960 --> 00:19:08.970
It's possible to, in fact, invade the name
servers.

00:19:08.970 --> 00:19:14.280
And so getting digital signatures that you
can use to confirm the binding of a domain

00:19:14.280 --> 00:19:16.940
name and address is actually an important
and useful step.

00:19:16.940 --> 00:19:19.610
It doesn't solve all problems.
But it's an important one.

00:19:19.610 --> 00:19:23.790
That's starting to happen now.
The root zone will be, in fact, signed sometime

00:19:23.790 --> 00:19:27.340
during the summer this year.
And then, finally, the routing system has

00:19:27.340 --> 00:19:32.570
the awkward problem that it's possible to
lie about what you're connected to.

00:19:32.570 --> 00:19:37.550
And if you want to avoid having -- introducing
lies into the routing tables, one way to do

00:19:37.550 --> 00:19:42.990
that is to have tables that show which entities,
which autonomous systems are allowed to announce

00:19:42.990 --> 00:19:46.530
what connectivity they have.
If it turns out that you received a routing

00:19:46.530 --> 00:19:51.620
update which isn't confirmed by a digitally
signed entry in a table that should be publicly

00:19:51.620 --> 00:19:55.620
available, you might discard that particular
update and maybe even raise a red flag and

00:19:55.620 --> 00:20:00.780
say somebody is trying to spoof the system
into directing traffic where it doesn't belong.

00:20:00.780 --> 00:20:04.360
There are sensored networks that are coming
up and being connected to the net.

00:20:04.360 --> 00:20:08.670
I'm give you an example.
The smart grid is an activity that we are

00:20:08.670 --> 00:20:11.910
very much involved with because we have a
power meter program.

00:20:11.910 --> 00:20:16.060
I'm personally involved in this in a variety
of ways because the smart grid interoperability

00:20:16.060 --> 00:20:21.620
panel has a governing board and I'm on that,
and the whole point here is to try to find

00:20:21.620 --> 00:20:27.180
ways of letting electricity-consuming devices
be more cooperative in the event you're reaching

00:20:27.180 --> 00:20:31.200
a peak load.
One of the ways is to go through the Internet.

00:20:31.200 --> 00:20:38.000
So they will be, increasingly, on the network.
And, finally, mobiles, as you all know.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:41.490
We have a bunch of problems -- I'm not going
to catalogue all the problems.

00:20:41.490 --> 00:20:44.690
I'm not going to talk you through all of them.
Because you know most of them.

00:20:44.690 --> 00:20:49.080
The thing I want to emphasize here is that
as soon as you turn a system like this over

00:20:49.080 --> 00:20:52.560
to the general public, you have to deal with
the general public.

00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:55.881
You have to deal with the motivations of the
general public.

00:20:55.881 --> 00:21:01.470
And not everyone in the general public necessarily
has everyone else's best interests in mind.

00:21:01.470 --> 00:21:09.680
And so one of the facts of life is that the
network began with a fairly homogeneous, uniform

00:21:09.680 --> 00:21:15.400
collection of academic types, research types,
engineer types, who more or less shared a

00:21:15.400 --> 00:21:18.940
common view of what it was they were trying
to accomplish, and they more or less trusted

00:21:18.940 --> 00:21:24.670
each other to do the right thing.
We are now faced with the consequences of

00:21:24.670 --> 00:21:28.390
commercialization.
And spread of the Net to the general public.

00:21:28.390 --> 00:21:33.540
Now, I was a big proponent in 1988 of commercializing
the Internet.

00:21:33.540 --> 00:21:36.260
And I know my colleagues, many of them, anyway,
thought I was crazy.

00:21:36.260 --> 00:21:40.600
Why would you let the general public, you
know, this great unwashed, into our wonderful,

00:21:40.600 --> 00:21:43.830
you know, sandbox?
And the honest answer to that is that I didn't

00:21:43.830 --> 00:21:48.740
think it would ever be available to the general
public if we didn't build a commercial engine

00:21:48.740 --> 00:21:52.960
underneath it to support it.
And so I was very much in favor of trying

00:21:52.960 --> 00:21:59.620
to find commercial businesses models that
would allow the Internet to grow, because

00:21:59.620 --> 00:22:02.260
the general public and industry wanted to
be on it.

00:22:02.260 --> 00:22:05.240
So, indeed, that's what happened.
I'm not trying to claim any credit.

00:22:05.240 --> 00:22:12.700
Just for having been much -- an advocate of
that particular thing happening.

00:22:12.700 --> 00:22:18.180
So the point I also want to make here is that
in spite of all the vulnerabilities and everything

00:22:18.180 --> 00:22:24.750
else -- and these are not just technical vulnerabilities
 -- you know, bad passwords, social engineering,

00:22:24.750 --> 00:22:29.210
and things of that sort -- some of the worst
things that happen to the Internet are mistakes

00:22:29.210 --> 00:22:32.670
that we make.
You know, half the Net falls off the Net,

00:22:32.670 --> 00:22:37.580
or YouTube disappears because somebody in
Pakistan creates a black hole that everyone

00:22:37.580 --> 00:22:40.570
routes to, not just the routers that are in
Pakistan.

00:22:40.570 --> 00:22:44.060
It's amazing how we can screw things up without
even trying.

00:22:44.060 --> 00:22:48.590
And so one of the big problems with design
of systems like this is how to make them more

00:22:48.590 --> 00:22:53.420
resilient and more conscious of errors in
configuration.

00:22:53.420 --> 00:22:56.400
This is probably one of the hardest problems
that I can think of.

00:22:56.400 --> 00:22:59.460
It's figuring out that a configuration is
wrong.

00:22:59.460 --> 00:23:04.200
It's easy if some part of that configuration
has a parameter value which is outside of

00:23:04.200 --> 00:23:06.410
a valid range.
That's the easy case.

00:23:06.410 --> 00:23:12.600
The hard case is some ensemble of configuration
parameters that turn out to add up to bad

00:23:12.600 --> 00:23:15.650
things.
Figuring out that that's the case, at least

00:23:15.650 --> 00:23:21.130
in my experience, is very, very difficult.
So that's a problem worthy of serious thought

00:23:21.130 --> 00:23:26.190
and consideration.
There are other serious security weaknesses

00:23:26.190 --> 00:23:30.170
in the system.
We have operating systems that are much too

00:23:30.170 --> 00:23:37.110
willing to be invaded, in effect, to allow
their resources to be attacked or coerced.

00:23:37.110 --> 00:23:42.731
Browsers which are very naive about software
that they download or that -- the Web pages

00:23:42.731 --> 00:23:46.331
they download and then interpret.
That's why we released Chrome, because we

00:23:46.331 --> 00:23:52.840
think we did a better job of building sandboxes
for the interpretation of downloaded Web pages.

00:23:52.840 --> 00:23:58.450
But we are still far from having what I consider
to be a completely secure environment.

00:23:58.450 --> 00:24:03.501
We never will.
But we can probably improve beyond where we

00:24:03.501 --> 00:24:06.050
are now.
We don't have very good access control practices.

00:24:06.050 --> 00:24:10.290
I talked about improper configurations.
A lot of the botnets that cause trouble, that

00:24:10.290 --> 00:24:14.270
generate spam, do denial of service attacks
and everything else are a direct consequence

00:24:14.270 --> 00:24:22.420
of laptops and PCs and increasingly now mobiles
that have been coerced and invaded and become

00:24:22.420 --> 00:24:28.900
tools of the botnet herders.
So even trying to detect and go after botnets

00:24:28.900 --> 00:24:34.890
is -- is going after the symptom.
The real issue is that we allow these resources

00:24:34.890 --> 00:24:39.880
to be coerced by people who don't own them
and have no business using the cycles.

00:24:39.880 --> 00:24:44.950
And, of course, there are all kinds of parties,
including organized crime and state-sponsored

00:24:44.950 --> 00:24:50.580
agencies, that want to exploit these vulnerabilities
in the network for their own advantage.

00:24:50.580 --> 00:24:54.070
There are lots of privacy problems.
And, again, they cover the gamut.

00:24:54.070 --> 00:24:59.570
And I want to get -- because it's already
20 minutes into this thing, I want to get

00:24:59.570 --> 00:25:05.070
beyond the list of problems and get to the
things that we really need to do.

00:25:05.070 --> 00:25:11.190
I do want to mention cloud collaboration.
That is to say, interactions between clouds.

00:25:11.190 --> 00:25:15.309
This is important to us because we are committed
to data liberation.

00:25:15.309 --> 00:25:18.120
We're committed to letting people get data
out of the cloud.

00:25:18.120 --> 00:25:23.010
The question is, how do they get it out?
First of all, where do they put it?

00:25:23.010 --> 00:25:26.630
And second, if they want to move it to another
cloud, how do they do that?

00:25:26.630 --> 00:25:32.360
And without going into terribly long diatribe
here, I believe that cloud interaction in

00:25:32.360 --> 00:25:37.820
2010 is about where we were with networking
in 1973.

00:25:37.820 --> 00:25:40.860
We had networks.
They were proprietary.

00:25:40.860 --> 00:25:45.380
You could make all the IBM machines interact
with each other, the Digital machines interact

00:25:45.380 --> 00:25:50.180
with each other using DECnet.
But we did not have much interaction between

00:25:50.180 --> 00:25:55.150
networks of different manufacturers.
Internet was intended as a nonproprietary

00:25:55.150 --> 00:25:59.070
solution to that problem.
Today we have proprietary clouds.

00:25:59.070 --> 00:26:01.930
In fact, most of the clouds have no idea that
other clouds exist.

00:26:01.930 --> 00:26:08.790
The best they can see is another cloud possibly
because it looks like a Web server somewhere.

00:26:08.790 --> 00:26:12.830
But clouds have properties.
And the different clouds that are built have

00:26:12.830 --> 00:26:16.740
different properties.
Some of you just go back into history for

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:20.470
a moment, will remember a protocol called
TELNET.

00:26:20.470 --> 00:26:25.420
TELNET had a very interesting property.
It had a thing called a network virtual terminal.

00:26:25.420 --> 00:26:29.470
This was a thing that never existed.
The problem was that the computers at the

00:26:29.470 --> 00:26:34.680
time had a whole variety of different terminals,
and they all had different encoding schemes

00:26:34.680 --> 00:26:38.980
and different conventions for what new line
is and so on.

00:26:38.980 --> 00:26:43.800
So the guys doing the ARPANET said why don't
we invent a thing which doesn't really exist

00:26:43.800 --> 00:26:47.420
but we'll call it a network virtual terminal.
It has a set of properties.

00:26:47.420 --> 00:26:51.940
We will map our terminals on a given host
into that network virtual terminal behavior.

00:26:51.940 --> 00:26:57.120
And what we would like to do is to say, for
everyone who's out on the Net, as long as

00:26:57.120 --> 00:27:01.380
you can handle the network virtual terminal,
then you can interact with any terminal on

00:27:01.380 --> 00:27:05.860
 -- any host in the ARPANET.
Maybe we need a network virtual cloud.

00:27:05.860 --> 00:27:09.500
We need something that all clouds can pretend
to be.

00:27:09.500 --> 00:27:15.850
It won't exercise every functional capability
of every cloud, but it might exercise sufficient

00:27:15.850 --> 00:27:19.059
commonality that we can move data back and
forth.

00:27:19.059 --> 00:27:23.890
Maybe we're capable of actually getting processes
to run in two clouds that are interacting

00:27:23.890 --> 00:27:29.290
with each other concurrently.
What about data that's in a cloud and it's

00:27:29.290 --> 00:27:32.660
access-controlled and we want to move it to
another cloud?

00:27:32.660 --> 00:27:36.690
What metadata do we have to move to the other
cloud and how will it be interpreted and will

00:27:36.690 --> 00:27:41.410
that access control continue to be observed?
These are all questions that don't yet have

00:27:41.410 --> 00:27:45.880
answers or maybe, in some cases, too many
different answers, because we have so many

00:27:45.880 --> 00:27:53.559
different options, you know, SOAP and UDDP
and all -- UDDI and so on from the Web world,

00:27:53.559 --> 00:27:59.630
and a variety of other options.
So we don't have any agreed standards on letting

00:27:59.630 --> 00:28:03.000
clouds interact with each other.
So I think there's a rich area for research

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:07.420
and development there.
So here are the kinds of problems that we

00:28:07.420 --> 00:28:10.511
did not solve and have not solved adequately
in the Net.

00:28:10.511 --> 00:28:15.610
One of security at all levels in the architecture.
There's no one place in the Net where you

00:28:15.610 --> 00:28:20.610
can guarantee all the security you need.
We don't actually have a very good understanding

00:28:20.610 --> 00:28:27.610
of the statistical nature of the network.
In fact, it's very hard, I think, to characterize

00:28:27.610 --> 00:28:33.540
the Internet or even pieces of it in a statistical
way, because unlike the telephone system,

00:28:33.540 --> 00:28:36.900
the dynamic range of demand on the Net is
extremely broad.

00:28:36.900 --> 00:28:40.000
You could be clicking a mouse for a little
while, sending almost no data at all, and

00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:43.420
the next thing you know, it's a 150-megabit
file transfer.

00:28:43.420 --> 00:28:48.130
Unlike the telephone system, where no matter
how much you talk, you can only consume 64

00:28:48.130 --> 00:28:51.429
kilobits per second on average, not counting
compression.

00:28:51.429 --> 00:28:57.450
So erelong formulas for the Net that will
help you design pieces are hard to come by.

00:28:57.450 --> 00:29:00.980
There are lots of debates about whether there
should be quality of service mechanisms in

00:29:00.980 --> 00:29:04.120
the network.
Right now all we have is best efforts.

00:29:04.120 --> 00:29:08.530
And there are valid arguments that sometimes
you want more than best efforts.

00:29:08.530 --> 00:29:13.080
The problem is, you can't rely on everybody
wanting to or being capable of offering more

00:29:13.080 --> 00:29:15.320
than that.
So the question is, how do you build that

00:29:15.320 --> 00:29:20.790
in so that multiple networks can somehow participate
in anything other than best effort?

00:29:20.790 --> 00:29:24.580
I mentioned Internationalized Domain Names.
Distributed algorithms.

00:29:24.580 --> 00:29:30.360
I don't think that we have done a very, very
good job in the R &amp; D community of developing

00:29:30.360 --> 00:29:32.590
distributed algorithms.
There are some.

00:29:32.590 --> 00:29:37.100
The routing algorithms are an example.
Their stability is sometimes in question.

00:29:37.100 --> 00:29:41.200
We do a lot of distributed computation, but
it's more like parallel stuff; right?

00:29:41.200 --> 00:29:47.520
When we do a search, it's, you know, one engine
is running the search algorithm.

00:29:47.520 --> 00:29:55.179
We don't have a lot of stuff going on in parallel
except for the fact that we can do our searches

00:29:55.179 --> 00:30:00.100
by splitting the data up into a large number
of different places and letting everybody

00:30:00.100 --> 00:30:05.000
run in parallel.
There aren't very many examples of distributed

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:07.250
algorithms that work well.
Some of ours are wonderful.

00:30:07.250 --> 00:30:13.740
Presence, which showed up originally in chat
kinds of things, could be quite rich in its

00:30:13.740 --> 00:30:16.400
character.
It's not just whether you're online or not

00:30:16.400 --> 00:30:19.700
online, but where are you online or what are
you doing online.

00:30:19.700 --> 00:30:23.850
These are all kinds of variations in Presence
that we can exploit.

00:30:23.850 --> 00:30:30.309
We've done a rotten job of dealing with mobility.
If there's anything that I think we really

00:30:30.309 --> 00:30:38.600
messed up, it's that.
The problem that happened is that the example

00:30:38.600 --> 00:30:43.490
of mobile in the original Internet design
was the packet radio network.

00:30:43.490 --> 00:30:47.180
This was a mobile network that was operating
here in the San Francisco Bay Area.

00:30:47.180 --> 00:30:53.010
We had some radio store and forward repeaters
up in the mountaintops and we had mobile devices

00:30:53.010 --> 00:31:01.290
down on the Bayshore freeway or driving around
Palo Alto and Mountain View and so on.

00:31:01.290 --> 00:31:09.110
The network itself took care of dealing with
the mobility of the devices below the Internet

00:31:09.110 --> 00:31:12.400
Protocol layer.
It's not too different from what happens with

00:31:12.400 --> 00:31:17.250
mobiles today, because what happens in a mobile
today is that the binding of the telephone

00:31:17.250 --> 00:31:20.561
number happens below the level of the phone
number.

00:31:20.561 --> 00:31:25.570
The consequence of that is that I thought,
wrongly, that we had dealt with the mobile

00:31:25.570 --> 00:31:28.210
problem.
I didn't take into account that a device,

00:31:28.210 --> 00:31:33.900
a host on the network, might actually move
physically from one place to another.

00:31:33.900 --> 00:31:37.810
Because at the time, they were big computer
centers that didn't get up and move around.

00:31:37.810 --> 00:31:42.340
Well, now they're in your pocket or maybe
they're even a chip that you've got inserted

00:31:42.340 --> 00:31:50.360
in your arm or it's in the dog.
So the problem here is that I failed to recognize

00:31:50.360 --> 00:31:55.290
that we might actually have nodes whose I.P.
addresses had to change depending on where

00:31:55.290 --> 00:32:00.160
they were accessing the network.
If we had -- I'll give you an example of possible

00:32:00.160 --> 00:32:04.990
kinds of solutions.
Multihoming, we did a terrible job of multihoming.

00:32:04.990 --> 00:32:10.040
Because every port on the computer had a different
I.P. address.

00:32:10.040 --> 00:32:15.250
It wasn't as if we had an address of the device
and then, you know, spokes pointing out.

00:32:15.250 --> 00:32:19.429
Every one of them had a different I.P. address.
That means that if you are getting service

00:32:19.429 --> 00:32:23.890
from two different ISPs, it's not exactly
clear that you can set up a TCP/IP connection

00:32:23.890 --> 00:32:30.290
with packets flowing along both of those in
order to assemble them together as one stream.

00:32:30.290 --> 00:32:34.990
Broadcast is another rant.
We did a terrible job of dealing with broadcast

00:32:34.990 --> 00:32:37.380
media.
In fact, we turned broadcast media into point-to-point

00:32:37.380 --> 00:32:41.650
links.
Think about 802.11, for example.

00:32:41.650 --> 00:32:47.020
So I would love to see some serious effort
put into, for example, a satellite system

00:32:47.020 --> 00:32:52.150
that could rain I.P. packets down on 100 million
receivers at the same time.

00:32:52.150 --> 00:32:56.450
For information that everybody wants, that
has a large number of interested recipients,

00:32:56.450 --> 00:33:00.080
broadcast is really good stuff.
And we don't do that.

00:33:00.080 --> 00:33:03.400
We're busy, you know, with these point-to-point
TCP connections.

00:33:03.400 --> 00:33:06.950
We do that with YouTube, we do that with a
lot of other applications.

00:33:06.950 --> 00:33:11.140
And I imagine if we were trying to pump out
a large number of software updates, it would

00:33:11.140 --> 00:33:15.820
be really nice if everybody would say, okay,
at 8:00, we're all going to listen for the

00:33:15.820 --> 00:33:20.860
next update of the -- of that software, and
then I only have to transmit it once.

00:33:20.860 --> 00:33:22.840
Okay.
Some people would have to say, hey, I missed

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:26.490
a couple of packets.
Please send them to me on a unicast basis.

00:33:26.490 --> 00:33:30.880
But the bulk of the delivery could be done
very, very efficiently.

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:37.270
So I want to keep going here.
Another huge issue is identity, authentication,

00:33:37.270 --> 00:33:40.760
and authorization.
Those are all three different things.

00:33:40.760 --> 00:33:45.880
We don't do a very good job of authenticating
the components of the network.

00:33:45.880 --> 00:33:49.360
We don't know whether a router over there
is really one that we should be talking to

00:33:49.360 --> 00:33:53.820
or not.
There isn't any built-in, inherent ability

00:33:53.820 --> 00:33:56.450
in the Net to authenticate various sources
and syncs.

00:33:56.450 --> 00:34:03.309
And if I were doing this over again, I would
have wanted to put in tools for strong authentication.

00:34:03.309 --> 00:34:08.290
This doesn't mean that I believe that anonymity
is a bad thing or that it should be banned

00:34:08.290 --> 00:34:11.530
or anything like that.
I think anonymity is important.

00:34:11.530 --> 00:34:16.570
But there are times when you really need to
know what it is that you're interacting with

00:34:16.570 --> 00:34:20.889
at various layers in the protocol.
So if we're having a simple little chat, I

00:34:20.889 --> 00:34:25.210
may not care exactly who you are.
But if you say, "I want to borrow $50,000,"

00:34:25.210 --> 00:34:30.040
I care a lot more about who you are and whether
you can pay me back and how do I find you

00:34:30.040 --> 00:34:35.300
again.
So authenticity and identification turn out

00:34:35.300 --> 00:34:39.080
to be really important.
And I would submit to you that for Google's

00:34:39.080 --> 00:34:44.909
own range of applications, that investing
in good-quality identity and authentication

00:34:44.909 --> 00:34:49.139
is really important, because that's the only
way we will convince people that it's okay

00:34:49.139 --> 00:34:53.860
to use the cloud, that we have a strong way
of identifying the users, and that we have

00:34:53.860 --> 00:34:58.350
a good way of preventing people from getting
access to information that they shouldn't

00:34:58.350 --> 00:35:02.100
have access to.
So we need these kinds of technologies to

00:35:02.100 --> 00:35:07.620
convince our users that it's safe to use the
cloud and that we know how to protect their

00:35:07.620 --> 00:35:12.230
information from others.
Well, okay.

00:35:12.230 --> 00:35:15.000
So multicore processors.
This is another little headache.

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:18.740
Moore's Law is broken.
The clock speed is not going up at the rate

00:35:18.740 --> 00:35:22.109
that it used to.
Now our problem is how do I use a larger number

00:35:22.109 --> 00:35:28.690
of cores running at a fixed clock speed.
I think a lot of algorithms don't know how

00:35:28.690 --> 00:35:33.210
to take advantage of that.
So this is another rich place for us to evolve

00:35:33.210 --> 00:35:37.380
our applications.
I'll come back to delay and disruption tolerance.

00:35:37.380 --> 00:35:41.980
Let me just say that in the mobile world,
one of the big problems is that you don't

00:35:41.980 --> 00:35:45.619
have guaranteed solid connectivity or reliable
connectivity.

00:35:45.619 --> 00:35:48.710
Frequently, it's interrupted.
Frequently, there's packet loss.

00:35:48.710 --> 00:35:52.430
And most of the algorithms in the Internet
are not as good as they could be and should

00:35:52.430 --> 00:36:01.200
be in order to overcome those problems.
Governance is a nontechnical problem space.

00:36:01.200 --> 00:36:07.740
Now, if you and I think that technical decisions
are hard, imagine what it takes to make political

00:36:07.740 --> 00:36:12.600
decisions associated with who's in charge
of what.

00:36:12.600 --> 00:36:17.310
These don't necessarily have quantitative
metrics.

00:36:17.310 --> 00:36:27.090
And so you wind up having to argue, coerce,
cajole, you know, demand and all these other

00:36:27.090 --> 00:36:32.480
things in order to come to some kind of agreements.
Sometimes they're international in character.

00:36:32.480 --> 00:36:35.850
Sometimes they're national in scope.
Sometimes they might be corporate.

00:36:35.850 --> 00:36:40.320
But governance questions are policy-related
questions, and they're very, very hard to

00:36:40.320 --> 00:36:42.070
deal with.
There's a bunch of them here.

00:36:42.070 --> 00:36:48.090
I won't go into any further detail there.
Finally, mobile operation again.

00:36:48.090 --> 00:36:54.580
What I would love to see, frankly, is some
ability to let a device move around from one

00:36:54.580 --> 00:37:01.140
termination point to another in I.P. terms
and still maintain its connectivity to the

00:37:01.140 --> 00:37:05.869
higher-level protocols.
There are some applications or protocols for

00:37:05.869 --> 00:37:09.340
that purpose that are being looked at in the
Internet Engineering Task Force.

00:37:09.340 --> 00:37:15.859
This was a mistake that I made, a really bad
one, that I didn't recognize at the time.

00:37:15.859 --> 00:37:24.100
When we split I.P. from TCP, I thought it
was very clever to use the I.P. address as

00:37:24.100 --> 00:37:30.770
part of the end-point connection identifier.
So TCP was bound very, very strongly to IP.

00:37:30.770 --> 00:37:34.180
And I was patting myself on the back, thinking,
"Look, I saved all these bits.

00:37:34.180 --> 00:37:38.930
I didn't have to have another set of identifiers
at the TCP or UDP layer."

00:37:38.930 --> 00:37:42.119
And I thought, boy, I was really smart, it
was very efficient, blah, blah, blah.

00:37:42.119 --> 00:37:47.780
Turns out to have been a bad mistake.
It screwed up multihoming, it screwed up mobility

00:37:47.780 --> 00:37:53.040
where I.P. addresses were changing.
Now, this leads to a different kind of a problem.

00:37:53.040 --> 00:37:58.800
Think about it for a moment, that you're moving
around and getting different I.P. addresses.

00:37:58.800 --> 00:38:03.091
And so at some point, you have an end-point
identifier distinct from the I.P. address,

00:38:03.091 --> 00:38:06.820
and you've established, let's say, a TCP connection
using those end-point identifiers.

00:38:06.820 --> 00:38:12.200
Now you move to a different I.P. location,
and you say to the other guy, hi, it's me

00:38:12.200 --> 00:38:15.380
again.
I'm just at a different I.P. address.

00:38:15.380 --> 00:38:20.730
Well, that looks like a hijack, doesn't it?
So the real question is, how do you reauthenticate

00:38:20.730 --> 00:38:24.900
so the guy on the other end says, well, I
know you said it's you, but, you know, can

00:38:24.900 --> 00:38:29.550
you take this encrypted challenge and send
it back to me properly encrypted in my public

00:38:29.550 --> 00:38:35.340
key, blah, blah, blah.
You need to have mechanisms that reestablish

00:38:35.340 --> 00:38:39.370
authentic trust between the two parties if
you're going to allow this kind of dynamics

00:38:39.370 --> 00:38:44.460
to happen.
We don't do a very good job of routing in

00:38:44.460 --> 00:38:47.770
general.
But more importantly, in the mobile world,

00:38:47.770 --> 00:38:53.320
if topologies are changing, getting an routing
algorithm that works, when the topology keeps

00:38:53.320 --> 00:38:59.250
changing -- it's not just a question of it's
a fixed topology and links are up and down;

00:38:59.250 --> 00:39:03.581
this is a topology which is varying -- that
gets to be a really hard problem.

00:39:03.581 --> 00:39:08.340
And it hasn't been well solved in my view.
We don't even have the idea of persistent

00:39:08.340 --> 00:39:10.670
connections.
I can open up a connection and things are

00:39:10.670 --> 00:39:15.850
running, and I lose connectivity.
And when I come back again, I would like to

00:39:15.850 --> 00:39:20.210
reestablish the session that I had.
We don't have a session layer in the formal

00:39:20.210 --> 00:39:25.970
sense in the Internet architecture.
And that, too, might be a useful development.

00:39:25.970 --> 00:39:29.400
And then, finally, in the mobile world, there
is a great deal of interest in being able

00:39:29.400 --> 00:39:31.780
to self-organize.
You throw a bunch of nodes down and they're

00:39:31.780 --> 00:39:36.560
wandering around and they discover each other.
This is all wonderful until you start worrying

00:39:36.560 --> 00:39:41.130
about the possibility that one of them isn't
supposed to be there because it's the bad

00:39:41.130 --> 00:39:44.030
guy.
And if you have a self-organizing network,

00:39:44.030 --> 00:39:47.020
the bad guy might look like a good guy because
you didn't know the difference.

00:39:47.020 --> 00:39:49.740
So he's part of your environment and all of
a sudden you have a problem.

00:39:49.740 --> 00:39:53.900
So figuring out who are the good guys and
the bad guys in a self-organizing network

00:39:53.900 --> 00:39:58.609
are -- that's a particularly interesting problem.
In the military world, this is called the

00:39:58.609 --> 00:40:01.450
overrun problem.
I have a whole bunch of nodes, they were all

00:40:01.450 --> 00:40:04.359
okay.
Then the bad guys overran the good guys and

00:40:04.359 --> 00:40:09.090
the bad guys got ahold of their devices and
said, hi, we're still good guys.

00:40:09.090 --> 00:40:13.570
And, of course, they're not, but they're taking
advantage of your assets to defeat you.

00:40:13.570 --> 00:40:19.119
So figuring out how to make that all work
in a way that is reliable and trustworthy

00:40:19.119 --> 00:40:23.280
is tricky.
Performance.

00:40:23.280 --> 00:40:26.221
Well, the original Internet design was best
efforts.

00:40:26.221 --> 00:40:30.160
And here I'm going to invoke Greg Chesson.
He is back there.

00:40:30.160 --> 00:40:32.640
Wave your hand.
You doesn't have any hair, either.

00:40:32.640 --> 00:40:37.770
You don't have your tee shirt on, though.
So Greg --

00:40:37.770 --> 00:40:42.900
&gt;&gt;&gt; That's the -- Greglers.
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: You get two points for that.

00:40:42.900 --> 00:40:48.910
Very good.
So Greg is, like a lot of our senior management,

00:40:48.910 --> 00:40:53.780
intensely concerned with performance, particularly
inside the data centers.

00:40:53.780 --> 00:41:00.950
And so what I want to observe to you is that
for a long time, performance on the Internet

00:41:00.950 --> 00:41:06.910
was not as -- was not viewed as critical as
just getting it to work at all.

00:41:06.910 --> 00:41:10.440
And so now we're at the point where this thing
has been around for a long time and every

00:41:10.440 --> 00:41:14.810
one of us and our customers and users are
relying on this thing working reliably and

00:41:14.810 --> 00:41:19.470
quickly.
One of the things I want to emphasize to you

00:41:19.470 --> 00:41:25.080
is that I am not an I.P. bigot.
I'm not a TCP bigot.

00:41:25.080 --> 00:41:28.450
Just because I happen to have been involved
in designing and building that stuff does

00:41:28.450 --> 00:41:34.619
not mean that it is the place to stop.
It means it might be the end of the beginning.

00:41:34.619 --> 00:41:38.510
But the important thing is here that none
of you should be afraid to say, maybe we should

00:41:38.510 --> 00:41:42.490
do something different.
That's not irreligious.

00:41:42.490 --> 00:41:45.051
Or heretical.
I know I'm the Internet evangelist.

00:41:45.051 --> 00:41:50.310
But, you know, I feel like the Pope and the
heretic.

00:41:50.310 --> 00:41:53.660
Right?
The real answer here is that you should not

00:41:53.660 --> 00:41:57.869
be afraid to think differently, to branch
out into new areas, to think about things

00:41:57.869 --> 00:42:05.470
that may not even be compatible.
When people think about what might come next,

00:42:05.470 --> 00:42:09.920
they think, oh, how in the hell are we ever
going to deploy this in the existing Internet?

00:42:09.920 --> 00:42:14.640
And I would remind you that before the Internet,
there was this big network called the telephone

00:42:14.640 --> 00:42:18.720
network.
And you could have said, how in the heck would

00:42:18.720 --> 00:42:21.670
you ever deploy the Internet?
We already have a global network.

00:42:21.670 --> 00:42:24.540
It's called the telephone net.
You'd never be able to do this.

00:42:24.540 --> 00:42:28.900
Well, it did take a few decades.
But it happened.

00:42:28.900 --> 00:42:33.609
And there's no reason why it couldn't happen
again with good ideas that work better.

00:42:33.609 --> 00:42:39.691
So I want to somehow, if I can empower you
to not be afraid to think differently.

00:42:39.691 --> 00:42:44.359
And Greg I know already is fully capable of
doing that, because he's got ideas inside

00:42:44.359 --> 00:42:51.170
our data center that work better than the
conventional TCP mechanisms.

00:42:51.170 --> 00:42:54.400
We have -- this is not an entirely internal
meeting.

00:42:54.400 --> 00:42:56.970
We have some folks from outside.
So we're not going to go into any details

00:42:56.970 --> 00:43:02.200
about that, unless Greg chooses to.
But the point I want to make is that this

00:43:02.200 --> 00:43:06.099
guy is fearless.
He's looking at, you know, 80 gigabits a second

00:43:06.099 --> 00:43:10.820
worth of traffic going in two different directions
to figure out what the heck is going on inside

00:43:10.820 --> 00:43:16.210
the TCP.
And he's done a brilliant job of making this

00:43:16.210 --> 00:43:20.170
work a lot better.
Now, there is another area of real interest

00:43:20.170 --> 00:43:23.210
here.
Addresses in the Internet are bound mostly

00:43:23.210 --> 00:43:27.780
to edge devices.
And Bob Kahn and I have had this long-standing

00:43:27.780 --> 00:43:33.930
debate about what should have an address.
Why should we stop at the box?

00:43:33.930 --> 00:43:36.270
Could we talk about the things that are inside
the box?

00:43:36.270 --> 00:43:39.700
What about logical addresses of objects that
are inside the box?

00:43:39.700 --> 00:43:43.780
Should the routing tables be able to route
not to a box, but to something inside that

00:43:43.780 --> 00:43:47.590
might move around?
Well, I don't have an answer to you.

00:43:47.590 --> 00:43:52.369
But I can tell you that thinking about addressing
other than just termination at a box may turn

00:43:52.369 --> 00:43:56.990
out to be a very rich way of dealing with
some of the cloud issues that we face, because

00:43:56.990 --> 00:44:01.440
the data in the cloud is what has to move
around.

00:44:01.440 --> 00:44:07.250
So this means, by the way, that the domain
name system may not necessarily be the sole

00:44:07.250 --> 00:44:09.820
means of binding an identifier to an I.P.
address.

00:44:09.820 --> 00:44:14.619
And this is another example of don't be afraid
to think differently.

00:44:14.619 --> 00:44:20.430
So instead of using DNS, it may very well
be that some other label which has a different

00:44:20.430 --> 00:44:27.590
meaning than the DNS might be useful and might
be worthwhile implementing in addition to

00:44:27.590 --> 00:44:32.450
or even instead of the DNS.
So the DNS isn't necessarily fixed in the

00:44:32.450 --> 00:44:37.430
universe of Internet architecture.
I'm going to skip over policy considerations

00:44:37.430 --> 00:44:43.230
in the interest of time here.
I do want to bring up a couple of other major

00:44:43.230 --> 00:44:48.960
problems, though, for us at Google.
Intellectual property treatment is troublesome,

00:44:48.960 --> 00:44:55.680
because the history has been rooted in hard
copy of things.

00:44:55.680 --> 00:45:04.390
In fact, if you read the copyright law, it
talks about the fixing of a work in a physical

00:45:04.390 --> 00:45:09.940
manifestation.
So it's a CD, or it's a tape, or it's a hard

00:45:09.940 --> 00:45:15.220
drive, or it's a memory stick, or a book,
or a magazine.

00:45:15.220 --> 00:45:20.540
And when we start dealing with digital information,
we have to cope with the fact that, A, it's

00:45:20.540 --> 00:45:27.670
easy to replicate, and, B, it's easy to distribute.
And the notion of controlling copies as the

00:45:27.670 --> 00:45:35.080
means of recovering value from intellectual
property collides with this ease of distribution

00:45:35.080 --> 00:45:37.570
and copying.
In fact, if you think about the way the Web

00:45:37.570 --> 00:45:42.810
works in particular, what does a router do?
The first thing it does is go out and copy

00:45:42.810 --> 00:45:47.150
whatever the home page is on the Web site.
It's a giant copying engine.

00:45:47.150 --> 00:45:51.800
No wonder the people who think of intellectual
property protection as controlling copies

00:45:51.800 --> 00:45:58.150
are a little unnerved by this, you know, global
spread of this giant copying machine.

00:45:58.150 --> 00:46:06.730
It's, you know, sort of Xerox written large.
So the problem here is that the current rules

00:46:06.730 --> 00:46:13.300
are rooted in the wrong kind of concepts.
And we really need to rethink how people can

00:46:13.300 --> 00:46:20.380
recover value from intellectual property in
addition to or instead of simply controlling

00:46:20.380 --> 00:46:22.330
copies.
Now, I don't have a magic answer for you here.

00:46:22.330 --> 00:46:28.000
I mean, the usual easy one is, well, just
encrypt everything and then sell people the

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:31.070
keys.
Yeah, that's all fine, unless somebody buys

00:46:31.070 --> 00:46:34.270
one key and puts it up on the Net.
And then everybody has a copy to it, and so

00:46:34.270 --> 00:46:38.170
much for that.
I would point out, however, even in that scenario,

00:46:38.170 --> 00:46:43.820
that somebody who puts the key up is -- morally,
 -- has morally created a copyright violation

00:46:43.820 --> 00:46:49.020
of the same order of magnitude as making copies
of music CDs or making copies of books and

00:46:49.020 --> 00:46:51.840
distributing them.
The problem, of course, might be finding that

00:46:51.840 --> 00:46:58.410
person in order to somehow inhibit that sort
of behavior.

00:46:58.410 --> 00:47:02.060
The semantic Web is something that Tim Berners-Lee
I know has been working on very hard.

00:47:02.060 --> 00:47:09.240
In fact, it came up in the CIO meetings that
we hosted here yesterday.

00:47:09.240 --> 00:47:15.220
This problem is that there is a lot of unstructured
information on the Web right now.

00:47:15.220 --> 00:47:20.010
But there's also a lot of structured information,
except that we can't see it, because it isn't

00:47:20.010 --> 00:47:22.680
expressed in a form that the crawler can detect
it.

00:47:22.680 --> 00:47:27.680
So when we have a lot of structured data,
it's kind of like dark matter in the universe.

00:47:27.680 --> 00:47:31.280
We know it's there but we can't quite detect
it.

00:47:31.280 --> 00:47:36.140
So there's dark information in the Internet.
And finding a way to make it more visible

00:47:36.140 --> 00:47:41.980
so that our crawlers can find it and our users
can discover it is a nontrivial exercise.

00:47:41.980 --> 00:47:47.400
We have to find ways of labeling content that's
consistent across a large number of different

00:47:47.400 --> 00:47:50.080
bins full of information.
This is a hard thing.

00:47:50.080 --> 00:47:56.130
It's the data dictionary collision problem
for people who speak databases.

00:47:56.130 --> 00:48:04.369
The other two things on this slide have to
do with my recurring nightmare that our digital

00:48:04.369 --> 00:48:10.910
history will be lost in not very many years.
So let me give you the long-term example.

00:48:10.910 --> 00:48:14.430
It's the year 3000.
And you've just done a Google search.

00:48:14.430 --> 00:48:21.099
And you find a 1997 PowerPoint file.
That's even -- let's pretend you're using

00:48:21.099 --> 00:48:23.970
Windows 3000, just for the sake of argument.
[ Laughter ]

00:48:23.970 --> 00:48:28.380
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: The question is, does Windows
3000 know how to interpret a 1,000-year-old

00:48:28.380 --> 00:48:31.760
PowerPoint file.
And the chances are pretty good that it can't.

00:48:31.760 --> 00:48:37.710
The question is even if we were using open
source software, it isn't necessarily clear

00:48:37.710 --> 00:48:41.870
that the versions of the open source software
that we might be dealing with in the year

00:48:41.870 --> 00:48:46.090
3000 know how to interpret files that are
1,000 years old.

00:48:46.090 --> 00:48:50.480
The reason I'm so exercised about this is
not the thousand-year problem.

00:48:50.480 --> 00:48:53.960
It's the next year or the third or fourth
or fifth-year problem.

00:48:53.960 --> 00:49:00.710
I'm already seeing image formats that are
noninterprettable by current-day software.

00:49:00.710 --> 00:49:04.040
I see this happen a lot between the Macs and
the PCs.

00:49:04.040 --> 00:49:08.050
I do a presentation on a Mac and then show
it on a PC, and a big thing comes up saying

00:49:08.050 --> 00:49:13.170
"We don't know how to interpret this thing."
So it's a big blank in the slide.

00:49:13.170 --> 00:49:19.250
So I am worried that our descendents 100 years
from now or maybe even our kids 20 years from

00:49:19.250 --> 00:49:23.990
now won't actually have any idea what the
beginning of the 21st century was like, because

00:49:23.990 --> 00:49:29.800
none of the digital objects that we have created
and stored away are interpretable.

00:49:29.800 --> 00:49:34.880
So the question is how to solve that problem.
This is hard, because it's not just a question

00:49:34.880 --> 00:49:39.910
of hanging on to the application software.
If somebody says, "I'm not going to support

00:49:39.910 --> 00:49:45.930
that software anymore," and it runs on that
version of an operating system, is there any

00:49:45.930 --> 00:49:50.660
way that we can hang on to not only the application,
but the operating system it ran on and maybe

00:49:50.660 --> 00:49:54.500
the emulation of the hardware that the operating
system ran on that ran the application that

00:49:54.500 --> 00:50:03.410
knew how to interpret the complex bits?
The question is, what rules reasonably apply

00:50:03.410 --> 00:50:09.880
to, let's say, not coerce, but encourage people
to make sure that objects that were created

00:50:09.880 --> 00:50:15.880
in earlier forms are still interpretable?
And this gets all mixed up in motivations,

00:50:15.880 --> 00:50:22.320
in business ethics, in business practices,
and in intellectual property management.

00:50:22.320 --> 00:50:26.080
So if we don't do something about this in
a conscious way, we will end up with a lot

00:50:26.080 --> 00:50:29.770
of rotten bits that won't be interpretable.
And that can't be the right outcome.

00:50:29.770 --> 00:50:37.770
I am particularly personally embarrassed about
this because when I work with librarians and,

00:50:37.770 --> 00:50:42.190
you know, we walk in with our fancy CDs and
DVDs and everything else, they say, "How will

00:50:42.190 --> 00:50:44.990
these last?"
