00:54:12.900 --> 00:54:17.119
So we're going to have sensored networks everyone.
The data is going to be flowing to us.

00:54:17.119 --> 00:54:22.390
That's simply going to be another part of
our Internet universe, huge amounts of information

00:54:22.390 --> 00:54:27.310
either flowing to consumption places or devices
just talking back and forth to each other.

00:54:27.310 --> 00:54:29.630
Okay.
So last thing I want to do is quickly mention

00:54:29.630 --> 00:54:33.080
the Interplanetary Internet.
I know many of you have heard me talk about

00:54:33.080 --> 00:54:34.440
this.
I'm very excited about it.

00:54:34.440 --> 00:54:37.119
It's not a Google project.
We're not planning to take over the solar

00:54:37.119 --> 00:54:41.320
system as part of our business model, at least
not as far as I've been told.

00:54:41.320 --> 00:54:46.230
But I am interested in the problem of being
able to give richer communication for manned

00:54:46.230 --> 00:54:51.090
and robotic space exploration.
Some of this is driven by our visits to Mars

00:54:51.090 --> 00:54:57.400
with the Rovers and others -- since 1976,
actually, we've been sending equipment to

00:54:57.400 --> 00:55:01.360
Mars.
And most of the communication with the spacecraft

00:55:01.360 --> 00:55:05.550
have been with point-to-point links.
One of the things that my colleagues at the

00:55:05.550 --> 00:55:09.560
Jet Propulsion Lab and NASA have been wanting
is a richer networking environment so that

00:55:09.560 --> 00:55:14.450
we can support much more complex missions
with many different devices, lots of different

00:55:14.450 --> 00:55:19.200
orbiters, things on the ground that are moving
around, sensored networks that are self-organizing.

00:55:19.200 --> 00:55:25.910
So this is just a view of Google Mars, which
is a beautiful piece of work.

00:55:25.910 --> 00:55:33.360
What you might know is that when the Rovers
landed several years ago on Mars, the original

00:55:33.360 --> 00:55:38.930
plan was to transmit data direct to Earth.
And the radios overheated.

00:55:38.930 --> 00:55:43.820
And so they decided that they'd have to reduce
the duty cycle to keep the radios from damaging

00:55:43.820 --> 00:55:47.021
themselves.
And that reduced the data return, which is

00:55:47.021 --> 00:55:53.079
already rather limited at 28 kilobits a second.
Now, remember, these things are 35 million

00:55:53.079 --> 00:55:57.890
to 235 million miles away.
At the speed of light, it takes three and

00:55:57.890 --> 00:56:02.260
a half minutes for a signal to go from Earth
to Mars when we're closest together and 20

00:56:02.260 --> 00:56:05.710
minutes when we're farthest apart.
So my colleagues and I were thinking, okay,

00:56:05.710 --> 00:56:08.220
why don't we use Internet protocols.
It works here.

00:56:08.220 --> 00:56:10.480
It ought to work there.
And that's true.

00:56:10.480 --> 00:56:16.710
But it doesn't work very well in between.
Imagine TCP with flow control with a 40-minute

00:56:16.710 --> 00:56:19.619
round-trip time.
Then there's the other problem of celestial

00:56:19.619 --> 00:56:22.190
motion.
The planets are rotating, and we haven't figured

00:56:22.190 --> 00:56:23.540
out how to stop that, either.
[ Laughter. ]

00:56:23.540 --> 00:56:27.830
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: The problem is, there's a thing
on the surface of Mars, and it rotates around,

00:56:27.830 --> 00:56:29.609
and you can't talk to it until it comes back
around again.

00:56:29.609 --> 00:56:36.990
And the same thing happens with orbiters.
The Jet Propulsion Lab guy said, "We have

00:56:36.990 --> 00:56:40.710
orbiters around Mars already.
They were used to map the surface of Mars

00:56:40.710 --> 00:56:45.400
to decide where the Rover should land."
They reprogrammed the Rovers and the satellites

00:56:45.400 --> 00:56:50.589
to do store-and-forward relay back to Earth
at 128 kilobits a second using a different

00:56:50.589 --> 00:56:52.950
radio.
So store-and-forward is the way all the data

00:56:52.950 --> 00:56:57.410
has been coming back from Mars.
When the Phoenix lander arrived, in May of

00:56:57.410 --> 00:57:01.369
2008, it was going to the North Pole.
It didn't have any director or path.

00:57:01.369 --> 00:57:05.730
So they deliberately did store-and-forward.
So my colleagues and I thought, well, why

00:57:05.730 --> 00:57:07.369
don't we just use TCP.
But it doesn't work.

00:57:07.369 --> 00:57:11.329
So we had to invent a whole new suite of protocols
that we call Delay and Disruption Tolerant

00:57:11.329 --> 00:57:15.740
Networking Protocols.
Those not only have been made to work at interplanetary

00:57:15.740 --> 00:57:20.339
distances using the Epoxy spacecraft, which
is not on its way to rendezvous with a comet

00:57:20.339 --> 00:57:26.070
and will be using the new DTN protocols, but
it also has been applied to military tactical

00:57:26.070 --> 00:57:29.470
communications.
The Defense Advance Research Agency that funded

00:57:29.470 --> 00:57:34.400
the original interplanetary work and the original
Internet work has adapted these Delay and

00:57:34.400 --> 00:57:39.570
Disruption Tolerant Protocols to Tactical
Com, which is a highly hostile environment.

00:57:39.570 --> 00:57:43.640
So what we're hoping, frankly, is that the
standards that we have been developing for

00:57:43.640 --> 00:57:47.730
interplanetary communication will be adopted
by all the countries around the world.

00:57:47.730 --> 00:57:53.060
If they do, then everybody's spacecraft could
potentially interwork, which means when they

00:57:53.060 --> 00:57:58.250
have completed their initial missions, they
might well be repurposed to be part of an

00:57:58.250 --> 00:58:01.369
interplanetary backbone.
Over the course of the next several decades,

00:58:01.369 --> 00:58:05.941
assuming the standardization is adopted, we
may actually see an interplanetary backbone

00:58:05.941 --> 00:58:09.230
emerge out of the space exploration that goes
on.

00:58:09.230 --> 00:58:11.390
Okay.
So I really overshot my time.

00:58:11.390 --> 00:58:15.250
But let me stop here and invite questions.
I know we've got some Dory things.

00:58:15.250 --> 00:58:27.710
And in any event, thanks a whole bunch for
letting me take up an hour of your time.

00:58:27.710 --> 00:58:34.180
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;&gt; Let me read the first question on the

00:58:34.180 --> 00:58:38.740
Dory.
We have a lot of our distributed offices VCed

00:58:38.740 --> 00:58:41.940
in, including the West Coast, plus Boulder,
plus New York.

00:58:41.940 --> 00:58:47.619
So let's just get to one of those, at least.
Comcast recently had a court victory in their

00:58:47.619 --> 00:58:51.250
effort to own the Internet and control traffic
on it.

00:58:51.250 --> 00:58:55.570
Murdoch has similar ambitions.
And I suspect that the military will make

00:58:55.570 --> 00:58:59.520
a similar claim.
Can a free and open Internet be effectively

00:58:59.520 --> 00:59:02.460
defended?
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: Wait a minute.

00:59:02.460 --> 00:59:09.170
I was too busy stabbing myself in the gut
here.

00:59:09.170 --> 00:59:11.859
Wow.
Okay.

00:59:11.859 --> 00:59:17.310
So I don't think that Comcast quite had the
victory that's characterized here.

00:59:17.310 --> 00:59:24.010
What they basically said was, when the FCC
told us that we should cease and desist interfering

00:59:24.010 --> 00:59:29.640
with BitTorrent, that the FCC didn't have
a basis for making that demand.

00:59:29.640 --> 00:59:34.080
Now, you need to have a little context.
A few years ago, Internet was considered a

00:59:34.080 --> 00:59:38.931
telecommunications service and it was regulated
in what's called Title II of the Telecom Act,

00:59:38.931 --> 00:59:46.750
as amended in 1996.
In its infinite wisdom, FCC, upon hearing

00:59:46.750 --> 00:59:54.790
debates between the telcos and the cable companies
on the differences in their regulation, said,

00:59:54.790 --> 00:59:58.560
"I hear you.
We realize that you are regulated differently,

00:59:58.560 --> 01:00:02.810
but you're both offering Internet service.
We are going to move Internet service into

01:00:02.810 --> 01:00:09.119
what's called Title I of the Telecom Act."
This is essentially applications.

01:00:09.119 --> 01:00:13.900
It's an information service.
And it was treated as a vertically integrated

01:00:13.900 --> 01:00:21.240
service, so there was no notion of telecommunications.
There was no notion of common carriage anymore,

01:00:21.240 --> 01:00:30.440
because it was treated as this unitary thing.
Well, within Title I, the court ruled that

01:00:30.440 --> 01:00:36.900
the FCC did not have any authority deriving
from that title that would allow them to tell

01:00:36.900 --> 01:00:41.300
Comcast to cease and desist.
Now, I want to defend Comcast just a little

01:00:41.300 --> 01:00:46.099
bit here.
What they had -- what was happening to them

01:00:46.099 --> 01:00:50.040
is that they have an asymmetric network; right?
You can't push data into the cable system

01:00:50.040 --> 01:00:53.340
as quickly as you can pull it out.
So they're faced with a problem with people

01:00:53.340 --> 01:00:57.849
doing BitTorrent, because some people who
are running multiple TCP connections to do

01:00:57.849 --> 01:01:02.190
the BitTorrent application are consuming much
more bandwidth than everybody else.

01:01:02.190 --> 01:01:06.540
So they're kind of freezing everybody out.
So Comcast is saying, well, we have to do

01:01:06.540 --> 01:01:11.099
something to make it more fair for everyone
to get access to the limited resources that

01:01:11.099 --> 01:01:15.021
we can make available.
And their way of doing the network management

01:01:15.021 --> 01:01:18.200
was, let me say, not very ept.
They --

01:01:18.200 --> 01:01:23.860
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: -- chose to do deep-packet inspections,

01:01:23.860 --> 01:01:28.890
see which guys were doing the BitTorrent protocol
and then generate fake reset messages to both

01:01:28.890 --> 01:01:33.579
people, leaving them both thinking the other
guy hung up.

01:01:33.579 --> 01:01:37.880
That was a particularly crude way of trying
to do network management.

01:01:37.880 --> 01:01:44.430
In subsequent conversations with them, I urged
them to consider an alternative, which was

01:01:44.430 --> 01:01:49.829
to look at the bandwidth that was being consumed
by these parties in a, you know, nonprotocol-centric

01:01:49.829 --> 01:01:55.329
way and simply limit the amount of bandwidth
that anybody could get if the system had gone

01:01:55.329 --> 01:01:57.800
into congestion.
And that, as I understand it, is what they

01:01:57.800 --> 01:02:03.609
have chosen to do.
So the court case basically says to the FCC

01:02:03.609 --> 01:02:10.260
that Title I may not be a very good way of
preserving fairness and choice for users.

01:02:10.260 --> 01:02:13.250
What do we want?
At Google, what we want is every user has

01:02:13.250 --> 01:02:17.190
the ability to go anyplace on the Internet
and run any applications that he or she wants

01:02:17.190 --> 01:02:21.762
to.
We understand that it's not right for a user

01:02:21.762 --> 01:02:25.069
to get more resource than they are paying
for.

01:02:25.069 --> 01:02:29.099
We understand that people have to do some
network management to deal with, you know,

01:02:29.099 --> 01:02:35.660
potential denial of service attacks, to deal
with fair allocation of the resources.

01:02:35.660 --> 01:02:44.640
But we don't want them to abuse their access
to and control over a broadband conduit that

01:02:44.640 --> 01:02:49.100
gets the consumer into Internet services.
In particular, for example, if you're a cable

01:02:49.100 --> 01:02:53.930
company that's offering television as a service
and you're being paid for that, and you're

01:02:53.930 --> 01:02:59.349
also offering Internet, broadband Internet
service, and you're being paid for that, we

01:02:59.349 --> 01:03:05.730
wouldn't want YouTube, for example, to be
somehow interfered with over the Internet

01:03:05.730 --> 01:03:10.020
part of the channel in order to favor the
other application that that company offers.

01:03:10.020 --> 01:03:12.660
Now, I'm not picking on Comcast or any other
cable company.

01:03:12.660 --> 01:03:20.240
I'm just saying that we are looking for fair
and equitable access for users and for suppliers

01:03:20.240 --> 01:03:26.839
of service on those underlying broadband facilities.
The likely outcome of this particular situation

01:03:26.839 --> 01:03:35.069
is that the FCC will choose to reclassify
Internet service as a Title II kind of service.

01:03:35.069 --> 01:03:39.840
Some of you who know anything about this could
conceivably levitate skyward, because there

01:03:39.840 --> 01:03:45.510
are a huge number of things in Title II that
are all about telephony, all about universal

01:03:45.510 --> 01:03:49.069
service and taxation and tariffing and all
this stuff.

01:03:49.069 --> 01:03:57.990
The FCC has the ability to forbear from applying
some of the possible controls, remedies, and

01:03:57.990 --> 01:04:02.300
regulations in Title II.
They always have the freedom not to do something.

01:04:02.300 --> 01:04:07.470
And so if anything does happen to reclassify
Internet as Title II, my hope and expectation

01:04:07.470 --> 01:04:12.940
is that only a small number of the terms and
conditions of Title II would apply to the

01:04:12.940 --> 01:04:15.550
Internet service.
One of the things I'm very attracted to is

01:04:15.550 --> 01:04:19.200
common carriage.
Common carriage basically says you have to

01:04:19.200 --> 01:04:24.430
apply the same rules to everybody, all customers
are served under the same terms and conditions.

01:04:24.430 --> 01:04:28.130
There is no favoritism.
And I think that's important for our business.

01:04:28.130 --> 01:04:29.520
Okay.
Next Dory question.

01:04:29.520 --> 01:04:31.869
I don't know how to --
&gt;&gt;&gt; How about if we --

01:04:31.869 --> 01:04:34.460
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: There we go.
Why don't I read it.

01:04:34.460 --> 01:04:38.869
That way, I'll pay attention.
That's terrible, isn't it?

01:04:38.869 --> 01:04:42.470
How would the Internet be different if there
had been native support early on for user

01:04:42.470 --> 01:04:46.010
identification and for content signing and
for encryption?

01:04:46.010 --> 01:04:49.160
This turned out to be hard to be retrofit.
Yeah, it has been hard.

01:04:49.160 --> 01:04:56.099
I actually think it would have been very helpful
and powerful not only to have users able to

01:04:56.099 --> 01:05:01.150
authenticate themselves, but have devices
able to say, yes, I'm getting control from

01:05:01.150 --> 01:05:06.839
somebody I recognize.
I will accept the exchange or demand for information.

01:05:06.839 --> 01:05:10.090
I wish that we had done that.
The problem is, the technology to do it wasn't

01:05:10.090 --> 01:05:17.790
available at the time that the Internet standards
were being finalized in 1978.

01:05:17.790 --> 01:05:23.290
Public key crypto was invented in 1977 by
Whit Diffie and Marty Hellman at Stanford.

01:05:23.290 --> 01:05:28.170
And I knew all about what they were doing.
But it was an idea at the time.

01:05:28.170 --> 01:05:33.710
It wasn't -- RSA hadn't been implemented yet.
So by the time those things matured, the Internet

01:05:33.710 --> 01:05:40.310
had raced on into, you know, such a deployment
that we couldn't force those things in.

01:05:40.310 --> 01:05:43.660
If we were doing it over again, I would have
wanted to have the advantage of that.

01:05:43.660 --> 01:05:46.319
Okay.
How long did the government want to keep TCP/IP

01:05:46.319 --> 01:05:49.079
a secret technology?
Zero milliseconds.

01:05:49.079 --> 01:05:52.599
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: Never.

01:05:52.599 --> 01:05:54.589
And I have to tell you, I'm really proud of
this.

01:05:54.589 --> 01:06:01.800
Bob and I, Bob Kahn and I, deliberately set
about to make TCP/IP visible to the public,

01:06:01.800 --> 01:06:06.619
to anyone in the world.
We visibly wanted it to be unconstrained,

01:06:06.619 --> 01:06:10.510
fully accessible, fully documented from the
get-go.

01:06:10.510 --> 01:06:14.990
And the reason is very simple.
Our rationale was that if -- this was ever

01:06:14.990 --> 01:06:20.349
going to be an international standard, if
it was ever going to be adopted by the proprietary

01:06:20.349 --> 01:06:24.000
community, there had to be zero barriers,
no excuses.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:28.080
You can't say, well, we couldn't get the documentation,
or, no, we didn't have access to a reference

01:06:28.080 --> 01:06:33.109
implementation.
Our conclusion was, make this so available

01:06:33.109 --> 01:06:35.820
that there are no excuses for not adopting
it.

01:06:35.820 --> 01:06:39.470
And we didn't put any patent constraints on
it.

01:06:39.470 --> 01:06:43.240
We didn't do anything other than to make it
fully and widely available.

01:06:43.240 --> 01:06:47.950
And I think that openness served us well,
because, ultimately, it did get adopted as

01:06:47.950 --> 01:06:54.120
an international standard.
What's the one thing you wish you had been

01:06:54.120 --> 01:06:59.790
 -- No -- oh, wish had been properly separated
into two or more things from the beginning.

01:06:59.790 --> 01:07:03.980
Well, the one thing I did mention was this
separation of identifier at the end points

01:07:03.980 --> 01:07:07.000
from the I.P. addresses.
I really wish I had done that.

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:10.890
By the way, we can still do that.
There is absolutely nothing stopping us from

01:07:10.890 --> 01:07:17.220
implementing protocols that have that property.
And, in fact, one of the things that is interesting

01:07:17.220 --> 01:07:19.800
about the Internet is that you can keep changing
it.

01:07:19.800 --> 01:07:25.420
You can keep adding new capabilities.
And I hope that we actually get there someday

01:07:25.420 --> 01:07:28.400
so that we have this flexibility that we don't
have today.

01:07:28.400 --> 01:07:32.839
How do I get this little thing to scroll down?
There we go.

01:07:32.839 --> 01:07:36.960
Okay.
What's -- Let's see.

01:07:36.960 --> 01:07:41.500
Something to think about at the end of the
discussion: If the Internet's original design

01:07:41.500 --> 01:07:46.109
had been different in the ways we've discussed,
how would its evolution have been different?

01:07:46.109 --> 01:07:49.900
Boy, that's a DNA question, isn't it, as opposed
to a DNS question.

01:07:49.900 --> 01:07:51.589
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: I know.

01:07:51.589 --> 01:07:58.340
Bad -- minus 2.
Well, I think probably, if we had done some

01:07:58.340 --> 01:08:03.339
of the things I suggested, we would have had
strong authentication available to make the

01:08:03.339 --> 01:08:07.810
system a little more secure.
We would have had better mobility, multihoming,

01:08:07.810 --> 01:08:12.369
ability to use multiple routes to push data
across the Net faster, taking advantage of

01:08:12.369 --> 01:08:18.779
multiple paths at the same time.
I think we might have had a good shot at making

01:08:18.779 --> 01:08:24.859
the network more resistant to various forms
of attack, because we had put in authentication

01:08:24.859 --> 01:08:30.139
in places where it could usefully be applied.
And, again, I want to remind you that it's

01:08:30.139 --> 01:08:33.449
not impossible to put some of those things
in again.

01:08:33.449 --> 01:08:37.849
There's an activity in the National Science
Foundation called FIND, Future Internet Design.

01:08:37.849 --> 01:08:46.089
And there are ideas that are being pursued
with support from NSF, some of which touch

01:08:46.089 --> 01:08:51.079
on the ideas I've talked about.
Some are even more elaborate than that.

01:08:51.079 --> 01:08:56.069
And there's nothing stopping us from trying
some of those ideas out, either in the existing

01:08:56.069 --> 01:08:59.609
Internet or, in fact, in something which is
independent.

01:08:59.609 --> 01:09:06.050
So my sense right now is that we are not constrained
to live the history of the network.

01:09:06.050 --> 01:09:09.539
We have the freedom and flexibility to change
that if we want to.

01:09:09.539 --> 01:09:13.699
Let's see.
What choices would you have made if you'd

01:09:13.699 --> 01:09:19.829
known that the Internet would eventually be
used for commercial purposes?

01:09:19.829 --> 01:09:24.489
I don't think I would have made different
choices, to be honest with you, since I was

01:09:24.489 --> 01:09:30.049
a big proponent of trying to turn various
parts of the network into commercially useful

01:09:30.049 --> 01:09:33.579
things.
I was very happy to see Cisco and Proteon

01:09:33.579 --> 01:09:38.339
and others make commercial routers.
Because the way we made routers before that

01:09:38.339 --> 01:09:42.259
was to take a computer and a graduate student
and wrap the graduate student around the router.

01:09:42.259 --> 01:09:44.389
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: And we were running out of graduate

01:09:44.389 --> 01:09:47.269
students.
So seeing commercially available routers was

01:09:47.269 --> 01:09:51.000
great.
And finally came Internet services that were

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:55.150
commercially available.
And that didn't happen until we broke a policy

01:09:55.150 --> 01:09:59.650
logjam in 1988.
I asked permission from the federal government

01:09:59.650 --> 01:10:04.120
to allow me to connect the commercial MCI
mail system to the Internet in 1988.

01:10:04.120 --> 01:10:09.639
Up until that time, 15 years of the Internet
program, nobody was allowed to put commercial

01:10:09.639 --> 01:10:13.969
bits on the government-sponsored backbone.
So I was really happy when they said, yes,

01:10:13.969 --> 01:10:18.230
you can do that.
Within a year, we had gotten the MCI mail

01:10:18.230 --> 01:10:20.840
system connected.
All the other e-mail providers said, wait

01:10:20.840 --> 01:10:24.159
a minute, those MCI guys shouldn't have that
privilege alone.

01:10:24.159 --> 01:10:28.500
So they jumped on, telemail, and Ontime, and
CompuServe, and so on.

01:10:28.500 --> 01:10:34.139
An odd side effect, they hadn't been able
to talk to each other before, because they

01:10:34.139 --> 01:10:37.219
were closed e-mail systems, but they could
all talk to the Internet.

01:10:37.219 --> 01:10:39.880
In consequence, they could talk to another
through the Internet.

01:10:39.880 --> 01:10:43.840
That was a surprise for everybody.
Holy cow, I just got a message from some guy

01:10:43.840 --> 01:10:46.289
on a different e-mail system.
How did that happen?

01:10:46.289 --> 01:10:52.480
The side effect of having allowed the commercial
use of the government-sponsored backbone is

01:10:52.480 --> 01:10:56.309
that commercial providers of service didn't
have to build their own backbone.

01:10:56.309 --> 01:11:00.920
So that meant they had a relatively low barrier
for offering commercial service that could

01:11:00.920 --> 01:11:03.709
use the government-sponsored backbones for
a time.

01:11:03.709 --> 01:11:07.840
It didn't take very long.
That was 1989 when we saw the first commercial

01:11:07.840 --> 01:11:13.999
Internet services come along.
By 1995, just a few years later, the National

01:11:13.999 --> 01:11:17.969
Science Foundation shut down the NSFNET because
it didn't need it anymore.

01:11:17.969 --> 01:11:22.719
It could buy, the universities could buy commercial
service more cheaply than they could get it

01:11:22.719 --> 01:11:24.940
from a specially operated network.
Sorry?

01:11:24.940 --> 01:11:29.780
Yes.
&gt;&gt;&gt; I asked this question a few weeks ago

01:11:29.780 --> 01:11:34.300
at TGIF, and I got completely shot down.
But --

01:11:34.300 --> 01:11:40.189
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: Can you use the microphone?
You'll be on record, by the way, so you should

01:11:40.189 --> 01:11:44.159
be aware of that.
&gt;&gt;&gt; But basically, I was just wondering what

01:11:44.159 --> 01:11:51.099
your thoughts were on where the Internet will
be in the future maybe ten, 50 years down

01:11:51.099 --> 01:11:54.869
the road, and what our relationship with the
technology will be then.

01:11:54.869 --> 01:11:59.200
I won't hold you to it.
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: That's a nice, simply-asked question

01:11:59.200 --> 01:12:03.699
with a really easy answer; right?
The short answer is, beats the hell out of

01:12:03.699 --> 01:12:07.090
me.
I wish I was eight years old so I could actually

01:12:07.090 --> 01:12:10.300
wait around to see the answer.
Honestly, I think two things.

01:12:10.300 --> 01:12:14.599
First of all, mobility, high bandwidth.
The network will disappear.

01:12:14.599 --> 01:12:17.659
You won't see it.
It will just be part of the environment in

01:12:17.659 --> 01:12:21.050
the same way that we don't think very much
about electrical power.

01:12:21.050 --> 01:12:23.739
We just plug into the wall and expect it to
be there.

01:12:23.739 --> 01:12:26.459
We will expect networking to be part of the
environment.

01:12:26.459 --> 01:12:32.170
It will always be available.
All of the devices that we use will be networkable.

01:12:32.170 --> 01:12:38.050
And the thing that I think is the most exciting
possibility is the possibility that the network

01:12:38.050 --> 01:12:43.989
will be able to interface to our neural systems.
Now, before you think I've gone all Ray Kurzweil

01:12:43.989 --> 01:12:49.590
on you.
I'm not quite there.

01:12:49.590 --> 01:12:54.170
But I will -- I need to finish with this comment,
even though there are other questions, because

01:12:54.170 --> 01:12:58.830
it's already way over time.
But I love to tell the story, many of you

01:12:58.830 --> 01:13:04.280
have heard this before, but I'll tell it anyway.
My wife was born with normal hearing, but

01:13:04.280 --> 01:13:07.630
she lost her hearing when she was three.
She had spinal meningitis.

01:13:07.630 --> 01:13:12.709
So she was deaf for 50 years.
Then she got a cochlear implant.

01:13:12.709 --> 01:13:17.689
Now, this is a device that interfaces to the
inner ear, the cochlea.

01:13:17.689 --> 01:13:22.260
It has electrodes that touch the auditory
nerve.

01:13:22.260 --> 01:13:28.610
The speech processor that she wears takes
in sound, does a Fourier transform to figure

01:13:28.610 --> 01:13:35.209
out what frequencies are present, then generates
electrical impulses in the inner ear to fake

01:13:35.209 --> 01:13:38.920
the brain out into thinking that the inner
ear is working.

01:13:38.920 --> 01:13:45.090
Now, the implication of that is that we understand
enough about sensorineural processes to imitate

01:13:45.090 --> 01:13:50.320
them electronically.
Now, I had been thinking, why not program

01:13:50.320 --> 01:13:54.659
 -- reprogram the speech processor so that
it can do TCP/IP?

01:13:54.659 --> 01:13:58.530
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: And now -- I'm not trying to

01:13:58.530 --> 01:14:02.949
get TCP/IP stuck in her brain.
We aren't there yet.

01:14:02.949 --> 01:14:09.189
But what I am interested in is the possibility
that she could ask a question, speak out loud,

01:14:09.189 --> 01:14:12.840
the microphones that normally are hearing
sound to help her hear could pick up what

01:14:12.840 --> 01:14:16.300
she says.
We could digitize that, packetize that, send

01:14:16.300 --> 01:14:20.499
it as voice-over-IP to a speech-understanding
processor.

01:14:20.499 --> 01:14:22.989
Guess what?
We make some of those; right?

01:14:22.989 --> 01:14:26.679
So she could ask a question.
The answer would come back through the Internet,

01:14:26.679 --> 01:14:31.119
go into the speech processor and go straight
up into her auditory nerve electronically

01:14:31.119 --> 01:14:34.179
and then, you know, the brain interprets that
as sound.

01:14:34.179 --> 01:14:39.230
So we could Internet-enable my wife.
That's pretty amazing.

01:14:39.230 --> 01:14:44.309
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Vint Cerf: So there -- I think, honestly,

01:14:44.309 --> 01:14:52.699
that our ability to network ourselves in the
sensory sense is quite likely.

01:14:52.699 --> 01:14:56.249
Whether we ever get cognitive interaction
is a whole other story.

01:14:56.249 --> 01:14:59.769
And it's one which is at the moment still
science fiction.

01:14:59.769 --> 01:15:05.510
But sensory, neural and sensory motor possibilities
are very strong.

01:15:05.510 --> 01:15:09.550
And, finally, something that you all know
about, augmented reality.

01:15:09.550 --> 01:15:15.249
When we think about things like my wife's
cochlear implant, this is remediating a problem

01:15:15.249 --> 01:15:17.469
that she had.
Otherwise, she can't hear.

01:15:17.469 --> 01:15:23.329
But there's no reason why we can't extend
the range of people's ability to sense the

01:15:23.329 --> 01:15:25.739
environment.
Why can't we see x-rays?

01:15:25.739 --> 01:15:29.229
Why can't we hear at the frequencies that
dogs can?

01:15:29.229 --> 01:15:32.360
There's no reason why we can't augment our
abilities.

01:15:32.360 --> 01:15:39.150
So I think if we're looking 30, 40, 50 years
into the future, we will see a lot of augmentation

01:15:39.150 --> 01:15:43.429
of our abilities, some of them sensory motor,
some sensory neural.

01:15:43.429 --> 01:15:47.719
Whether we ever get to the point where we
have cognitive interactions with computers,

01:15:47.719 --> 01:15:50.800
I don't know.
But I think it's very possible that we might

01:15:50.800 --> 01:15:56.719
have conversations with computers that are
richer than the ones that we have today, which

01:15:56.719 --> 01:16:03.780
are mostly command and control.
I think if you saw the TED lecture where the

01:16:03.780 --> 01:16:12.170
guy was wearing a projector and had a television
camera, he had a headset and a microphone,

01:16:12.170 --> 01:16:15.920
and instead of carrying a mobile around, he
carried a piece of paper.

01:16:15.920 --> 01:16:21.280
That was his display screen.
And he projected stuff onto the paper, or

01:16:21.280 --> 01:16:26.429
in one case he projected stuff on his hand.
It was the telephone dialing pad.

01:16:26.429 --> 01:16:30.739
And he dialed by just, you know, poking on
his hand.

01:16:30.739 --> 01:16:36.280
And, of course, what was going on is that
there was a video receiver that was watching

01:16:36.280 --> 01:16:41.280
the gesture and interpreting it.
This is the first time I have thought about

01:16:41.280 --> 01:16:47.939
and seen a computer-based system that was
participating in the same sensory environment

01:16:47.939 --> 01:16:50.940
that I am.
It's observing what I'm observing.

01:16:50.940 --> 01:16:56.619
It's seeing gestures and interpreting them.
So that kind of -- It was a really moving

01:16:56.619 --> 01:17:02.769
example of what happens when you let a computer
participate with you in the real world.

01:17:02.769 --> 01:17:08.070
If we see anything arrive out of that in 20
or 30 years' time, I bet it's going to be

01:17:08.070 --> 01:17:12.119
because we've got common, shared experiences
with our computers.

01:17:12.119 --> 01:17:13.869
Okay.
That's really all the time we've got.

01:17:13.869 --> 01:17:21.520
But thanks, again, for letting me be here
this afternoon.

01:17:21.520 --> 01:17:23.729
[ Applause ]

